for a comprehensive list of tox clients rather look at:
https://toktok.ltd/integrations.html
(which is more uptodate)

@ugintl c-toxcore is licensed under GPL, so any application using c-toxcore has to comply with GPL, which essentially forces those applications to be open source. So yes, Tox clients are opensource, and if there is a client which isn't - it's likely committing a license violation.

Some of our developers have looked into Tok and it appears like it's violating the license by not providing its users with the up-to-date source code of the application. It has also modified c-toxcore in some questionable ways, e.g. everyone using Tok's version of c-toxcore connects to Tok's bot, so Tok knows IP-to-Tox Id relation of everyone using it. I haven't looked into its code past that, so maybe there is more that it's doing. Other developers (I think it was @zugz?) have looked into Tok more than I, so they would know better. They have also requested Tok to provide the up-to-date source code multiple times, which resulted in nothing. It's really frustrating.

Anyone knowledgeable about this whole Tok thing willing to write a blog post about it? I have asked this on IRC before, but it didn't get anywhere.
